Cyber Threat Research
1. Phishing
Definition

Phishing is a cyber attack where attackers impersonate trusted organizations to steal sensitive information such as passwords, OTPs, or banking details.

Real-World Example

A fake email claiming to be from a bank asks users to click a malicious link and enter their login credentials.

Prevention
Verify email senders.
Avoid clicking unknown links.
Enable MFA.
Use spam filters.
2. Malware
Definition

Malware is malicious software designed to damage, disrupt, or gain unauthorized access to computer systems.

Real-World Example

The ILOVEYOU virus infected millions of computers through email attachments.

Prevention
Install antivirus software.
Download software only from trusted sources.
Keep software updated.
3. Ransomware
Definition

Ransomware encrypts files and demands payment to restore access.

Real-World Example

The WannaCry ransomware attack affected hospitals, businesses, and government organizations worldwide.

Prevention
Maintain regular backups.
Keep operating systems updated.
Avoid suspicious email attachments.
Use antivirus protection.
4. Social Engineering
Definition

Social engineering is the manipulation of people into revealing confidential information.

Real-World Example

A scammer pretends to be an IT support employee and asks for login credentials.

Prevention
Verify identities before sharing information.
Be cautious of unexpected requests.
Educate users about cyber scams.
5. Data Breach
Definition

A data breach occurs when unauthorized individuals gain access to confidential or sensitive information.

Real-World Example

The Equifax data breach exposed the personal information of millions of users.

Prevention
Use strong passwords.
Enable MFA.
Encrypt sensitive data.
Regularly update software.